Spring WebFlux — Reactive Web
    WebFlux is Spring's non-blocking, reactive web framework built on Project Reactor
    Uses Mono (0 or 1 item) and Flux (0 to N items) instead of plain objects and lists
    Runs on Netty by default (not Tomcat) — event loop model, not thread-per-request
    Best for high-concurrency I/O-bound workloads — chat, streaming, real-time data

WebFlux vs MVC — When to Choose:
    FEATURE              SPRING MVC                SPRING WEBFLUX
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Model                Imperative / blocking      Reactive / non-blocking
    Return types         Object, List, Page         Mono<T>, Flux<T>
    Server               Tomcat (thread per req)    Netty (event loop)
    Thread model         One thread per request     Few threads, event-driven
    DB support           JDBC, JPA (blocking)       R2DBC (reactive JDBC)
    Concurrency          Limited by thread pool     Handles 10x more concurrent
    Learning curve       Low — familiar Java        High — Reactor operators
    Best for             Standard CRUD APIs         Streaming, high concurrency
                         Existing JDBC code         Real-time, microservices
    Spring Security      Fully supported            Supported (different API)
    Testing              MockMvc                    WebTestClient
  
   THREADING MODEL DIFFERENCE:
  ────────────────────────────
  SPRING MVC (Tomcat)
  ────────────────────
  Request-1 → Thread-1 → [blocked waiting for DB] → Thread-1 → Response
  Request-2 → Thread-2 → [blocked waiting for DB] → Thread-2 → Response
  Request-3 → Thread-3 → [blocked waiting for DB] → Thread-3 → Response
  ...
  200 concurrent requests → 200 threads → memory pressure

  SPRING WEBFLUX (Netty)
  ───────────────────────
  Request-1 → EventLoop → [async DB call] → EventLoop → Response
  Request-2 → EventLoop → [async DB call] → EventLoop → Response
  Request-3 → EventLoop → [async DB call] → EventLoop → Response
  ...
  200 concurrent requests → 8 event-loop threads → low memory

