Reactive Operators — Quick Reference:
  TRANSFORM
  ──────────
  .map(item -> transform(item))            sync 1-to-1 transform
  .flatMap(item -> asyncOp(item))          async 1-to-1 (non-blocking)
  .flatMapMany(item -> flux)               Mono → Flux expansion
  .concatMap(item -> asyncOp(item))        flatMap but preserves order

  FILTER
  ───────
  .filter(item -> condition)               keep matching items
  .take(n)                                 first N items only
  .skip(n)                                 skip first N items
  .distinct()                              remove duplicates
  .limitRate(n)                            backpressure control

  COMBINE
  ────────
  Mono.zip(monoA, monoB, (a,b) -> ...)    combine two Monos
  Flux.merge(fluxA, fluxB)                merge two Fluxes (interleaved)
  Flux.concat(fluxA, fluxB)               fluxA completes, then fluxB
  Flux.zip(fluxA, fluxB)                  pair items by position

  ERROR HANDLING
  ───────────────
      .onErrorReturn(fallback)                 return fallback on error
      .onErrorResume(ex -> Mono.just(x))       switch to fallback Mono/Flux
      .onErrorMap(ex -> new CustomEx(ex))      translate exception type
      .retry(3)                                retry up to 3 times
      .retryWhen(Retry.backoff(3, ofMillis(100))) exponential backoff retry
      .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(5))          fail if no item within 5s

  SIDE EFFECTS (no data change)
  ──────────────────────────────
    .doOnNext(item -> log(item))             on each item
    .doOnError(ex -> alert(ex))              on error
    .doOnComplete(() -> notify())            on stream completion
    .doFinally(signal -> cleanup())          always — like finally

Complete Architecture — MVC + WebFlux Side by Side

  SPRING MVC STACK
  ─────────────────
  Client
    │ HTTP Request
    ▼
  Tomcat (thread pool — 200 threads default)
    │ assigns Thread-N to this request
    ▼
  DispatcherServlet
    │
    ▼
  HandlerMapping → finds @GetMapping method
    │
    ▼
  HandlerInterceptor.preHandle()
    │
    ▼
  @RestController method
    │ thread BLOCKS here waiting for DB
    ▼
  Service → Repository → JDBC → DB (blocking)
    │ thread unblocks, has result
    ▼
  Jackson serializes to JSON
    │
    ▼
  Response written — thread returned to pool
    │
    ▼
  Client receives response


  SPRING WEBFLUX STACK
  ─────────────────────
  Client
    │ HTTP Request
    ▼
  Netty (event loop — 8 threads for 8 cores)
    │ EventLoop-1 receives request, does NOT block
    ▼
  DispatcherHandler (reactive equivalent)
    │
    ▼
  HandlerMapping → finds handler
    │
    ▼
  WebFilter chain (reactive filter)
    │
    ▼
  @RestController / RouterFunction
    │ returns Mono/Flux — subscription deferred
    ▼
  R2DBC non-blocking DB call
    │ EventLoop-1 FREE to handle other requests
    │ ...handles 50 other requests meanwhile...
    │ DB responds → EventLoop-1 picks up signal
    ▼
  Reactor assembles result
    │
    ▼
  Jackson serializes reactively
    │
    ▼
  Client receives response

Best Practices

Use @RestController for all REST APIs — it combines @Controller and @ResponseBody
Always use constructor injection — never field @Autowired — makes testing easier and dependencies explicit
Use ResponseEntity when you need control over status code, headers, or conditional responses
Centralize exception handling in one @RestControllerAdvice class — never scatter try-catch in controllers
Validate at the controller boundary with @Valid — never trust incoming data
Use @PageableDefault to set sensible pagination limits — never return unbounded lists on GET all endpoints
Version your API from day one — changing an unversioned API breaks all existing clients
Never block in WebFlux — no Thread.sleep(), no .block(), no JDBC calls — use R2DBC
Use WebFlux functional style for complex routing logic — annotated style for simple CRUD
Choose MVC if you use JPA/JDBC — WebFlux + blocking drivers defeats the purpose entirely
Add spring-boot-starter-actuator to every service — /actuator/health and /actuator/metrics are free monitoring with zero code


In Spring WebFlux (the reactive, non-blocking part of the Spring Framework), Flux and Mono are the two primary building blocks. 
They both implement the Publisher interface from the Reactive Streams specification, but they represent different "cardinalities" of data.

Think of them as the reactive versions of a single object versus a collection.
1. Mono:
    A Mono is a specialized publisher that emits at most one item.
    Cardinality: 0 or 1.
    Behavior: It completes after emitting its single item. If there is no data, it completes as "empty."
    Analogy: A CompletableFuture<T> or an Optional<T>.
    Use Case: * Fetching a single user by ID (findById).
                An HTTP PUT or DELETE operation (where you return an empty Mono<Void>).
                Performing a single calculation.
2. Flux:
    A Flux is a publisher that can emit zero to N items.
    Cardinality: 0, 1, ..., ∞.
    Behavior: It can emit multiple items over time and then either complete successfully or trigger an error.
    Analogy: A reactive List<T> or a Stream<T> that stays open.
    Use Case: Fetching all users from a database (findAll).
              Streaming real-time data (like stock prices or Twitter feeds).
              Reading a large file line by line.

Feature                    Mono                                      Flux
Items Emitted              0 or 1                                    0 to Many (N)
Completion                 After 1st item or immediately if empty    "After the ""onComplete"" signal"
Standard Java Equivalent   Optional<T> / CompletableFuture            List<T> / Stream<T>
Typical Endpoint           GET /users/1                               GET /users

How They Work Together:
You can easily convert one into the other depending on your business logic requirements:
  Flux to Mono: If you have a Flux<User> and you only want the first user, you call .next(), which returns a Mono<User>.
                You can also use .collectList() to turn a Flux<T> into a Mono<List<T>>.
  Mono to Flux: If you have a Mono<User> and want to treat it as a stream, you call .flux().

The "Lazy" Factor
  Crucially, neither Flux nor Mono starts doing work until you subscribe. > "Nothing happens until you subscribe."
  In a WebFlux controller, you don't usually call .subscribe() yourself; the framework (Netty) does it for you when the HTTP request comes in.
      // Returning a single object
      public Mono<User> getUser(String id) {
          return userRepository.findById(id); 
      }

// Returning a stream of objects
public Flux<User> getAllUsers() {
    return userRepository.findAll(); 
}
